<subSubSection id="F7D86578FFAA1B1DFE2FF72802D54F56" pageId="20" pageNumber="170" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="BF7D36F3FFAA1B1DFE2FF72802D54F56" blockId="20.[438,1834,1689,2400]" pageId="20" pageNumber="170">
This species has a wide distribution from Java, Borneo, and 
<collectingCountry id="C7D57663FFAA1B1DF985F728002F4EF0" box="[1631,1833,2205,2246]" name="Philippines" pageId="20" pageNumber="170">Philippines</collectingCountry>
through the Malay Archipelago to Northern 
<collectingCountry id="C7D57663FFAA1B1DFABAF765010A4ECF" box="[1376,1548,2256,2297]" name="Australia" pageId="20" pageNumber="170">Australia</collectingCountry>
, also Hawaii. Although we did not rear this common longicorn, it doubtless breeds in dead stems of many kinds of plants in 
<collectingCountry id="C7D57663FFAA1B1DFC24F68303634F56" box="[1022,1125,2358,2400]" name="Guam" pageId="20" pageNumber="170">Guam</collectingCountry>
as it does in Hawaii.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
